Note:
This file implements expression parsing for Runa language expressions.

This file performs the following tasks:
- Parse arithmetic, logical, and comparison expressions using Pratt parser
- Handle ternary operator parsing (condition ? true_value : false_value) - v0.0.8.5 feature
- Process function calls and method invocations
- Handle expression precedence and associativity
- Support string interpolation parsing (f"text {expr}") - v0.0.8.5 feature
- Parse range expressions and member access

This file is essential because of the following reasons:
- Expression parsing is fundamental to Runa's computational capabilities
- Pratt parser ensures correct precedence and associativity handling
- Ternary operator is a key v0.0.8.5 feature requirement
- String interpolation enables dynamic string construction
- Proper expression parsing enables correct evaluation and code generation

This file consists of the following functions/features/operation types:
- Pratt parser implementation for expressions
- Ternary operator parsing and validation (v0.0.8.5)
- Function call and method invocation parsing
- String interpolation parsing (v0.0.8.5)
- Range expression and member access parsing
- Expression precedence and associativity handling

Dependencies:
- Imports parser.runa for parser state and token navigation
- Imports precedence.runa for operator precedence handling
- Imports ast_builder.runa for AST construction
- Imports lexical components for token recognition
- Imports memory/layout.runa for structure allocation
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/parsing/parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/frontend/parsing/precedence.runa" as Precedence
Import "compiler/frontend/parsing/ast_builder.runa" as ASTBuilder
Import "compiler/frontend/parsing/ast.runa" as AST
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_primitive.runa" as StringPrimitive
Import "compiler/frontend/lexical/lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/frontend/lexical/literals.runa" as Literals
Import "compiler/frontend/lexical/keywords.runa" as Keywords
Import "compiler/frontend/lexical/math_symbols.runa" as MathSymbols
Import "compiler/frontend/lexical/operators.runa" as Operators
Import "compiler/frontend/lexical/delimiters.runa" as Delimiters
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/lexical/token_constants.runa" as TokenConstants

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser-side token and context constants referenced by expression parsing.
Note: These mirror the lexical token codes (TOKEN_STRING -> string-literal class
Note: 100; TOKEN_EQUALS -> the '=' assignment token 600; the formatted/interpolated
Note: string tokens -> 102) and extend the parser's parsing-context enum with the
Note: argument-list / element-list contexts the error detector inspects.
Note: ============================================================================
Note: ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Note: Token-type constants — values EXACTLY mirror the authoritative lexer emit
Note: values. String/numeric/character literals arrive from the literal tokenizer
Note: (literals.runa 100-114, 140). Boolean and null/none/nil arrive as KEYWORDS
Note: (keywords.runa True 410 / False 411 / Null 420 / None 421 / Nil 422) because
Note: the lexer registers them in the keyword table — the literal-class boolean/null
Note: codes (120-132) are never emitted, so the parser must match the keyword codes.
Note: Identifier is the lexer.runa value 150 (distinct from the delimiter 200-210
Note: range — resolves the historical TOKEN_IDENTIFIER/TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN=200 collision).
Note: ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Note: String / formatted-string literal classes (literals.runa)
Note: Numeric literal classes (literals.runa)
Note: Boolean / null literals arrive as KEYWORDS (keywords.runa values)
Note: Identifier (lexer.runa)
Note: Lexer special tokens (lexer.runa)
Note: Delimiters (delimiters.runa)
Note: Operators (operators.runa)
Note: Keywords (keywords.runa)
Note: Pipeline / aggregation keywords (keywords.runa)
Constant CONTEXT_ARGUMENT_LIST as Integer is 6       Note: Inside a call argument list
Constant CONTEXT_ELEMENT_LIST as Integer is 7        Note: Inside a collection element list

Note: Precedence level of canonical "is ..." comparison phrases. Mirrors
Note: precedence.runa PRECEDENCE_COMPARISON (7) so the Pratt loop honours
Note: min_precedence when deciding whether to consume an "is" comparison.
Constant PRECEDENCE_COMPARISON_LEVEL as Integer is 7

Note: Precedence level of symbolic comparison operators (<, >, <=, >=). Mirrors
Note: precedence.runa PRECEDENCE_COMPARISON (7). Used by the with-call argument
Note: exclusion so a bare comparison terminates an argument rather than being
Note: absorbed into it.
Constant PRECEDENCE_COMPARISON_OP as Integer is 7

Note: Precedence level of symbolic equality operators (==, !=). Mirrors
Note: precedence.runa PRECEDENCE_EQUALITY (6). Used by the with-call argument
Note: exclusion so a bare equality test terminates an argument.
Constant PRECEDENCE_EQUALITY_OP as Integer is 6

Note: Minimum precedence used when parsing a single argument inside a
Note: canonical "with"-call argument clause. Mirrors precedence.runa
Note: PRECEDENCE_BITWISE_OR (3): it sits ABOVE logical-or (1) and logical-and
Note: (2) so the canonical "and" separator between arguments
Note: (`add with 20 and 22`) terminates the per-argument Pratt parse instead of
Note: being absorbed as a boolean operator, while still allowing bitwise (3-5),
Note: shift, additive and multiplicative operators to compose freely within one
Note: argument (`helper with a plus b`, `with r_bytes, m3 bitwise_and 15`).
Note: Comparison (7) and equality (6), though numerically above this floor, are
Note: explicitly terminated by the with-argument context exclusions below so a
Note: bare `helper with x is less than y` binds the comparison OUTSIDE the call,
Note: matching the stage1 monolith's arg chain (which skips both tiers). An
Note: argument that genuinely needs a top-level comparison, equality, or logical
Note: "and"/"or" must be parenthesised, matching the stage1 grammar's
Note: arg-context operator hierarchy.
Constant PRECEDENCE_WITH_ARGUMENT_LEVEL as Integer is 3

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Expression Parsing Entry Points
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "parse_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Parse an expression using Pratt parser algorithm
    
    Parameters:
      parser - Pointer to ParserState
   
    Returns:
      Pointer to expression AST node
      Returns 0 on parsing error
   
    Algorithm:
    1. Parse left operand using parse_primary_expression
    2. While current token is binary operator with precedence > 0:
       - Get operator precedence using Precedence.get_operator_precedence
       - If precedence > 0 (not ternary), parse binary expression
       - Otherwise, break (ternary handled separately)
    3. Check for ternary operator (? :)
    4. If ternary found, parse ternary expression
    5. Return final expression AST node
    :End Note
    
    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Parse with minimum precedence of 0 (parse everything)
    Let expression be proc parse_expression_with_precedence with parser, 0

    If expression is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check for ternary operator (? :) which has special handling
    Let current_token be proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser
    Let token_type be proc token_get_type from Parser with current_token

    Note: If question mark found, parse ternary expression
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_QUESTION_MARK:
        Let ternary be proc parse_ternary_expression with parser, expression
        Return ternary
    End If

    Return expression
End Process

Process called "parse_expression_with_precedence" takes parser as Integer, min_precedence as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Parse expression with minimum precedence constraint (Pratt parser core)
    
    Parameters:
      parser - Pointer to ParserState
      min_precedence - Minimum precedence level to parse
    
    Returns:
      Pointer to expression AST node
      Returns 0 on parsing error
    
    Pratt parser algorithm:
    1. Parse left operand using parse_primary_expression
    2. While current token is binary operator:
       - Get operator precedence
       - If precedence < min_precedence, break
       - If precedence == min_precedence and not left-associative, break
       - Parse binary expression with precedence + 1
    3. Return expression AST node
    :End Note

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Parse left operand (prefix expression or primary)
    Let current_token be proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser
    Let token_type be proc token_get_type from Parser with current_token

    Note: Result holder for the left operand. Declared up-front so the
    Note: canonical "bitwise not" prefix arm, the generic unary arm and the
    Note: primary arm can all assign it.
    Let left be 0

    Note:
    Canonical word-form unary bitwise NOT. The lexer tokenises the canonical
    phrase "bitwise not X" as TWO tokens — TOKEN_BITWISE (302) followed by
    TOKEN_NOT (382) — so neither the precedence table's unary entry (keyed on
    the symbolic ~ token TOKEN_BITWISE_NOT 533) nor the is_unary_operator check
    below fires for the bare TOKEN_BITWISE keyword in prefix position. Detect
    the phrase here and desugar it to "operand bitwise xor (-1)" — i.e. XOR with
    an all-ones mask, which is one's-complement — mirroring the stage1 monolith
    (which builds expression_create_binary_op(operand, bit_xor, -1)). This
    reuses the already-lowered binary XOR path (TOKEN_BITWISE_XOR 532 ->
    MIR 20012 -> LIR_XOR 30202) rather than introducing a parallel unary-NOT
    lowering. The operand is parsed at PRECEDENCE_UNARY so the prefix binds
    tighter than every binary operator, matching a real prefix operator.
    :End Note
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_BITWISE:
        Let not_disc_token be proc parser_peek_token from Parser with parser, 1
        Let not_disc_type be 0
        If not_disc_token is not equal to 0:
            Set not_disc_type to proc token_get_type from Parser with not_disc_token
        End If
        If not_disc_type is equal to TOKEN_NOT:
            Let not_op_line be proc token_get_line from Parser with current_token
            Let not_op_column be proc token_get_column from Parser with current_token

            Note: Consume "bitwise" and "not".
            proc parser_consume_token from Parser with parser
            proc parser_consume_token from Parser with parser

            Let not_operand be proc parse_expression_with_precedence with parser, PRECEDENCE_UNARY
            If not_operand is equal to 0:
                proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Expected expression after bitwise not", not_op_line, not_op_column
                Return 0
            End If

            Note: All-ones mask (-1) for the one's-complement XOR.
            Let not_mask be proc build_integer_literal from ASTBuilder with 0 minus 1, not_op_line, not_op_column
            If not_mask is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If

            Let not_node be proc build_binary_expression from ASTBuilder with TOKEN_BITWISE_XOR, not_operand, not_mask, not_op_line, not_op_column
            If not_node is equal to 0:
                proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Failed to create bitwise not AST node", not_op_line, not_op_column
                Return 0
            End If
            Set left to not_node
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check for unary operators (prefix)
    If left is equal to 0:
        Let is_unary be proc is_unary_operator from Precedence with token_type
        If is_unary is equal to 1:
            Set left to proc parse_unary_expression with parser
        Otherwise:
            Set left to proc parse_primary_expression with parser
        End If
    End If

    If left is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Parse binary operators with Pratt precedence climbing
    Loop forever:
        Set current_token to proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser
        Set token_type to proc token_get_type from Parser with current_token

        Note:
        Canonical comparison phrases begin with the particle "is" (TOKEN_IS),
        which the lexer emits as a standalone token and which is therefore NOT
        registered as a binary operator in the precedence table. Handle the full
        "is [not] {equal to | greater than [or equal to] | less than [or equal
        to] | within ...}" phrase here so the Pratt loop does not stop at "is"
        and silently truncate the condition (which previously dropped every
        If/While/For whose condition used a comparison). Comparison binds at
        PRECEDENCE_COMPARISON; respect the caller's min_precedence so chained
        operators associate correctly.
        :End Note
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IS:
            If PRECEDENCE_COMPARISON_LEVEL is less than min_precedence:
                Break
            End If
            Note:
            With-call argument context exclusion. A canonical "with"-call
            argument is parsed at PRECEDENCE_WITH_ARGUMENT_LEVEL so the "and"/","
            separators (logical level) terminate each argument while bitwise (3-5),
            shift (8), additive (9) and multiplicative (10) operators still compose
            inside one argument. Comparison (7) and equality (6) sit ABOVE the
            bitwise floor numerically, so a plain min_precedence floor would let
            `proc f from M with x, "ARC" is equal to 1` absorb the `is equal to 1`
            into the final argument and silently drop the enclosing comparison —
            leaving the If/While condition as the bare call (which then fails
            "Condition must be Boolean" in HIR lowering). The stage1 monolith's
            arg-context operator chain bottoms out ABOVE comparison/equality
            (parser_parse_arg_bit_and recurses straight into shift, skipping the
            comparison and equality tiers), so a comparison written without
            parentheses binds OUTSIDE the call. Mirror that here: when parsing a
            with-call argument, never consume a canonical "is ..." comparison.
            :End Note
            If min_precedence is equal to PRECEDENCE_WITH_ARGUMENT_LEVEL:
                Break
            End If
            Set left to proc parse_is_comparison with parser, left
            If left is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
            Continue
        End If

        Note:
        Canonical word-form bitwise shift binary operators. The lexer tokenises
        the canonical phrases "shifted left by" / "shifted right by" as THREE
        tokens — the TOKEN_SHIFTED keyword (304) followed by the direction
        discriminator TOKEN_LEFT (305) / TOKEN_RIGHT (306) and the connector
        TOKEN_BY (387) — so the precedence table (which keys single operator
        tokens) carries no entry for the bare TOKEN_SHIFTED keyword and the
        generic is_binary_operator check below rejects it, silently truncating
        the expression at "shifted". Handle the phrase here, mirroring the stage1
        monolith parser (parser.runa:865-924 parser_parse_shift): shift sits at
        PRECEDENCE_SHIFT (8) — TIGHTER than additive (+/- at 9 is numerically
        lower, but the monolith parses additive operands BELOW shift so a plain
        `a plus b shifted left by 1` groups as `(a plus b) shifted left by 1`),
        and WEAKER than no other word-operator level here; it binds tighter than
        the bitwise tiers (3-5) and comparison/equality (6-7). Both directions are
        left-associative. The discriminator and connector are peeked (not
        consumed) before min_precedence gating so the operator is rejected cleanly
        if the floor excludes it. The symbolic operator codes TOKEN_SHIFT_LEFT
        (534) / TOKEN_SHIFT_RIGHT (535) are stored in the binary AST node — those
        are exactly the codes the HIR/MIR binary-operator mapping recognises
        (534->20014 MIR_SHL, 535->20015 MIR_SHR), which lower through LIR_SHL
        (30300) / LIR_SHR (30301) to the x86_64 `shl` / `shr` instructions. `shr`
        is the logical (unsigned) right shift, matching the monolith's `shrq`
        for `shifted right by` (codegen.runa:3446-3453: right shift is logical by
        default per the language spec; arithmetic shift is expressed via
        `divided by 2^N`).
        :End Note
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SHIFTED:
            Let sh_dir_token be proc parser_peek_token from Parser with parser, 1
            Let sh_dir_type be 0
            If sh_dir_token is not equal to 0:
                Set sh_dir_type to proc token_get_type from Parser with sh_dir_token
            End If

            Let sh_by_token be proc parser_peek_token from Parser with parser, 2
            Let sh_by_type be 0
            If sh_by_token is not equal to 0:
                Set sh_by_type to proc token_get_type from Parser with sh_by_token
            End If

            Let sh_operator be 0
            If sh_dir_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT:
                Set sh_operator to TOKEN_SHIFT_LEFT
            End If
            If sh_dir_type is equal to TOKEN_RIGHT:
                Set sh_operator to TOKEN_SHIFT_RIGHT
            End If

            Note: A bare "shifted" not followed by left/right + by is not a shift
            Note: operator here (e.g. an identifier named "shifted"); stop the
            Note: Pratt loop so the surrounding context can handle the token.
            If sh_operator is equal to 0:
                Break
            End If
            If sh_by_type is not equal to TOKEN_BY:
                Break
            End If

            Note: Respect the caller's precedence floor (Pratt climbing). A shift
            Note: operator looser than the floor terminates this level.
            If PRECEDENCE_SHIFT is less than min_precedence:
                Break
            End If

            Note: Capture the operator position (the TOKEN_SHIFTED keyword) before
            Note: consuming the three phrase tokens.
            Let sh_op_line be proc token_get_line from Parser with current_token
            Let sh_op_column be proc token_get_column from Parser with current_token

            Note: Consume "shifted", the left/right direction, and "by".
            proc parser_consume_token from Parser with parser
            proc parser_consume_token from Parser with parser
            proc parser_consume_token from Parser with parser

            Note: Shift operators are left-associative: parse the right operand
            Note: one level tighter (precedence + 1) so chained operands at the
            Note: same level associate left-to-right.
            Let sh_right be proc parse_expression_with_precedence with parser, PRECEDENCE_SHIFT plus 1
            If sh_right is equal to 0:
                proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Expected expression after shift operator", sh_op_line, sh_op_column
                Return 0
            End If

            Let sh_node be proc build_binary_expression from ASTBuilder with sh_operator, left, sh_right, sh_op_line, sh_op_column
            If sh_node is equal to 0:
                proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Failed to create shift binary expression AST node", sh_op_line, sh_op_column
                Return 0
            End If

            Set left to sh_node
            Continue
        End If

        Note:
        Canonical word-form bitwise binary operators. The lexer tokenises the
        canonical phrases "bitwise and" / "bitwise or" / "bitwise xor" as TWO
        tokens — the TOKEN_BITWISE keyword (302) followed by the discriminator
        TOKEN_AND (380) / TOKEN_OR (381) / TOKEN_XOR (303) — so the precedence
        table (which keys single operator tokens) carries no entry for the bare
        TOKEN_BITWISE keyword and the generic is_binary_operator check below
        rejects it, silently truncating the expression at "bitwise". Handle the
        phrase here, mirroring the stage1 monolith's bit_or/bit_xor/bit_and
        precedence ladder: AND binds tightest (PRECEDENCE_BITWISE_AND = 5), then
        XOR (PRECEDENCE_BITWISE_XOR = 4), then OR (PRECEDENCE_BITWISE_OR = 3),
        all left-associative and all weaker than shift (8). The discriminator is
        peeked (not consumed) first so min_precedence can gate the operator
        before either token is eaten. The symbolic operator codes
        TOKEN_BITWISE_AND (530) / TOKEN_BITWISE_OR (531) / TOKEN_BITWISE_XOR
        (532) are stored in the binary AST node — those are exactly the codes the
        HIR/MIR binary-operator mapping recognises (530->20010, 531->20011,
        532->20012), so the node lowers to the correct bitwise machine op.
        :End Note
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_BITWISE:
            Let bw_disc_token be proc parser_peek_token from Parser with parser, 1
            Let bw_disc_type be 0
            If bw_disc_token is not equal to 0:
                Set bw_disc_type to proc token_get_type from Parser with bw_disc_token
            End If

            Let bw_precedence be 0
            Let bw_operator be 0
            If bw_disc_type is equal to TOKEN_AND:
                Set bw_precedence to PRECEDENCE_BITWISE_AND
                Set bw_operator to TOKEN_BITWISE_AND
            End If
            If bw_disc_type is equal to TOKEN_OR:
                Set bw_precedence to PRECEDENCE_BITWISE_OR
                Set bw_operator to TOKEN_BITWISE_OR
            End If
            If bw_disc_type is equal to TOKEN_XOR:
                Set bw_precedence to PRECEDENCE_BITWISE_XOR
                Set bw_operator to TOKEN_BITWISE_XOR
            End If

            Note: If the word after "bitwise" is not a recognised bitwise
            Note: discriminator (and/or/xor), this TOKEN_BITWISE does not open a
            Note: binary operator here (e.g. a stray keyword); stop the Pratt loop
            Note: so the surrounding context can handle the token.
            If bw_operator is equal to 0:
                Break
            End If

            Note: Respect the caller's precedence floor (Pratt climbing). A
            Note: bitwise operator looser than the floor terminates this level.
            If bw_precedence is less than min_precedence:
                Break
            End If

            Note: Capture the operator position (the TOKEN_BITWISE keyword) before
            Note: consuming the two phrase tokens.
            Let bw_op_line be proc token_get_line from Parser with current_token
            Let bw_op_column be proc token_get_column from Parser with current_token

            Note: Consume "bitwise" and the and/or/xor discriminator.
            proc parser_consume_token from Parser with parser
            proc parser_consume_token from Parser with parser

            Note: Bitwise operators are left-associative: parse the right operand
            Note: one level tighter (precedence + 1) so chained operands at the
            Note: same level associate left-to-right.
            Let bw_right be proc parse_expression_with_precedence with parser, bw_precedence plus 1
            If bw_right is equal to 0:
                proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Expected expression after bitwise operator", bw_op_line, bw_op_column
                Return 0
            End If

            Let bw_node be proc build_binary_expression from ASTBuilder with bw_operator, left, bw_right, bw_op_line, bw_op_column
            If bw_node is equal to 0:
                proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Failed to create bitwise binary expression AST node", bw_op_line, bw_op_column
                Return 0
            End If

            Set left to bw_node
            Continue
        End If

        Note:
        Underscore-spelled bitwise binary operators. Unlike the canonical
        spaced phrases ("bitwise and" / "bitwise or" / "bitwise xor"), the
        lexer scans the fused spellings `bitwise_and` / `bitwise_or` /
        `bitwise_xor` as a SINGLE TOKEN_IDENTIFIER (150) whose identity lives
        in its source spelling, not its type — so the precedence table carries
        no entry and the generic is_binary_operator check below rejects it,
        silently truncating the expression at the identifier (the
        `UNKNOWN/bitwise_and` first-marker observed in source_map.runa:705 and
        ~8 other modules). The monolith oracle (lexer.runa:1722-1727) lexes
        these words directly to the fused bit-operator tokens, so this arm must
        produce IDENTICAL parses to that oracle and to this parser's own
        spaced-form arm above. Reuse that arm's exact mapping: AND binds
        tightest (PRECEDENCE_BITWISE_AND = 5), then XOR
        (PRECEDENCE_BITWISE_XOR = 4), then OR (PRECEDENCE_BITWISE_OR = 3), all
        left-associative and all weaker than shift, with the symbolic operator
        codes TOKEN_BITWISE_AND (530) / TOKEN_BITWISE_OR (531) /
        TOKEN_BITWISE_XOR (532) stored in the binary AST node — exactly the
        codes the HIR/MIR binary-operator mapping recognises. The spelling is
        peeked (via primary_token_value_is, which null-guards the token and its
        value pointer) BEFORE consuming so min_precedence can gate the operator.
        The fused spelling `bitwise_not` is intentionally NOT recognised here:
        the monolith oracle does not lex it as an operator and every occurrence
        in the tree is a function/process name (e.g. `proc bitwise_not from
        BitwiseCore`), which must remain a plain identifier.
        :End Note
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
            Let uw_precedence be 0
            Let uw_operator be 0
            Let uw_is_and be proc primary_token_value_is with current_token, "bitwise_and"
            If uw_is_and is equal to 1:
                Set uw_precedence to PRECEDENCE_BITWISE_AND
                Set uw_operator to TOKEN_BITWISE_AND
            End If
            Let uw_is_or be proc primary_token_value_is with current_token, "bitwise_or"
            If uw_is_or is equal to 1:
                Set uw_precedence to PRECEDENCE_BITWISE_OR
                Set uw_operator to TOKEN_BITWISE_OR
            End If
            Let uw_is_xor be proc primary_token_value_is with current_token, "bitwise_xor"
            If uw_is_xor is equal to 1:
                Set uw_precedence to PRECEDENCE_BITWISE_XOR
                Set uw_operator to TOKEN_BITWISE_XOR
            End If

            Note:
            Short underscore spellings `bit_and` / `bit_or` / `bit_xor` are the
            same bitwise operations as the `bitwise_and` / `bitwise_or` /
            `bitwise_xor` forms above — the monolith oracle lexes them to
            TOKEN_BIT_AND/OR/XOR (lexer.runa:1710-1727) with identical semantics
            and precedence. They occur across ~50 self-host sites (file_io,
            and others). Map them to the same precedence + symbolic operator
            codes so they produce identical parses. (`bit_not`, like
            `bitwise_not`, is NOT an infix operator and stays a plain identifier
            / function name.)
            :End Note
            Let uw_is_and_s be proc primary_token_value_is with current_token, "bit_and"
            If uw_is_and_s is equal to 1:
                Set uw_precedence to PRECEDENCE_BITWISE_AND
                Set uw_operator to TOKEN_BITWISE_AND
            End If
            Let uw_is_or_s be proc primary_token_value_is with current_token, "bit_or"
            If uw_is_or_s is equal to 1:
                Set uw_precedence to PRECEDENCE_BITWISE_OR
                Set uw_operator to TOKEN_BITWISE_OR
            End If
            Let uw_is_xor_s be proc primary_token_value_is with current_token, "bit_xor"
            If uw_is_xor_s is equal to 1:
                Set uw_precedence to PRECEDENCE_BITWISE_XOR
                Set uw_operator to TOKEN_BITWISE_XOR
            End If

            Note: If the identifier is not one of the fused bitwise
            Note: operator spellings, it is an ordinary operand identifier; fall
            Note: through to the generic binary-operator handling below.
            If uw_operator is not equal to 0:
                Note: Respect the caller's precedence floor (Pratt climbing). A
                Note: bitwise operator looser than the floor terminates this level.
                If uw_precedence is less than min_precedence:
                    Break
                End If

                Note: Capture the operator position before consuming the token.
                Let uw_op_line be proc token_get_line from Parser with current_token
                Let uw_op_column be proc token_get_column from Parser with current_token

                Note: Consume the single fused operator identifier token.
                proc parser_consume_token from Parser with parser

                Note: Bitwise operators are left-associative: parse the right
                Note: operand one level tighter (precedence + 1) so chained
                Note: operands at the same level associate left-to-right.
                Let uw_right be proc parse_expression_with_precedence with parser, uw_precedence plus 1
                If uw_right is equal to 0:
                    proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Expected expression after bitwise operator", uw_op_line, uw_op_column
                    Return 0
                End If

                Let uw_node be proc build_binary_expression from ASTBuilder with uw_operator, left, uw_right, uw_op_line, uw_op_column
                If uw_node is equal to 0:
                    proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Failed to create bitwise binary expression AST node", uw_op_line, uw_op_column
                    Return 0
                End If

                Set left to uw_node
                Continue
            End If
        End If

        Note:
        Canonical string-concatenation operator `X joined with Y`. The lexer
        tokenises the phrase as TWO tokens — the TOKEN_JOINED keyword (560)
        followed by the particle TOKEN_WITH (372). TOKEN_JOINED IS registered
        in the precedence table at PRECEDENCE_ADDITIVE (9), so the generic
        binary-operator arm below would accept it — but that arm consumes only
        the single operator token (it has trailing-particle handling for
        "multiplied by"/"divided by"/"modulo by", NOT for "joined with"), so it
        would leave the "with" particle unconsumed and then fail the
        right-operand parse on it, dropping the whole enclosing statement. It
        also builds a generic binary node, whereas the construct must desugar to
        a string_concat(X, Y) call (the monolith oracle does this in
        parser.runa:1098-1112: parser_eat(JOINED), parser_eat(WITH), then
        expression_create_function_call("string_concat", {left,right}, 2)).
        Handle the phrase here, at the additive precedence level, left-
        associative — identical to the monolith's placement alongside +/-.

        The string_concat call node is built exactly as the print-statement
        comma-concatenation builder constructs it (statement_parsers.runa:4842-
        4849): a "string_concat" identifier callee plus a two-element positional
        argument list, via build_call_expression. The HIR lowers a call to the
        "string_concat" callable directly (hir_builder.runa:2755), so no new AST
        node type or lowering case is required; this reuses the already-proven
        print-port string_concat path.

        The monolith additionally marks the call with an int32 auto-stringify
        flag (Task #462) so its codegen can integer_to_string Integer operands.
        That flag lives at the monolith node's offset 4 — a free int32 slot
        BESIDE its int32 node_type at offset 0. The MODULAR node layout
        (ast.runa create_call_expression_node) stores node_type as a full 8-byte
        qword at offset 0, so offset 4 is the HIGH HALF of node_type, not a free
        flag — writing it would corrupt the node type. The modular backend has
        no auto-stringify reader (no int_proof side table) and every joined-with
        site in the compiler's own sources concatenates Strings or already-
        stringified `*_str` locals, so the flag is both unrepresentable in this
        layout and unnecessary here; it is intentionally omitted, producing the
        same node shape as the modular print-port concat builder.
        :End Note
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_JOINED:
            Note: Respect the caller's precedence floor (Pratt climbing). A
            Note: joined-with operator looser than the floor terminates this level.
            If PRECEDENCE_ADDITIVE is less than min_precedence:
                Break
            End If

            Note: Capture the operator position (the TOKEN_JOINED keyword) before
            Note: consuming the two phrase tokens.
            Let jw_op_line be proc token_get_line from Parser with current_token
            Let jw_op_column be proc token_get_column from Parser with current_token

            Note: Consume "joined".
            proc parser_consume_token from Parser with parser

            Note: Consume the mandatory "with" particle. Its absence means this
            Note: was not a well-formed joined-with phrase; report and abort so
            Note: the malformed expression does not silently mis-parse.
            Let jw_with_token be proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser
            Let jw_with_type be proc token_get_type from Parser with jw_with_token
            If jw_with_type is not equal to TOKEN_WITH:
                proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Expected 'with' after 'joined' in string concatenation", jw_op_line, jw_op_column
                Return 0
            End If
            proc parser_consume_token from Parser with parser

            Note: joined-with is left-associative: parse the right operand one
            Note: level tighter (precedence + 1) so chained `a joined with b
            Note: joined with c` associates left-to-right as
            Note: string_concat(string_concat(a, b), c).
            Let jw_right be proc parse_expression_with_precedence with parser, PRECEDENCE_ADDITIVE plus 1
            If jw_right is equal to 0:
                proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Expected expression after 'joined with'", jw_op_line, jw_op_column
                Return 0
            End If

            Note: Desugar to string_concat(left, jw_right): a "string_concat"
            Note: identifier callee plus a two-element positional argument list,
            Note: mirroring the print-port comma-concat builder and the
            Note: monolith's expression_create_function_call("string_concat",...).
            Let jw_callee be proc build_identifier_node from ASTBuilder with proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "string_concat", jw_op_line, jw_op_column
            If jw_callee is equal to 0:
                proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Failed to create string_concat callee identifier AST node", jw_op_line, jw_op_column
                Return 0
            End If
            Let jw_args be proc create from List
            If jw_args is equal to 0:
                proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Failed to create string_concat argument list", jw_op_line, jw_op_column
                Return 0
            End If
            proc list_append from List with jw_args, left
            proc list_append from List with jw_args, jw_right
            Let jw_node be proc build_call_expression from ASTBuilder with jw_callee, jw_args, 2, jw_op_line, jw_op_column
            If jw_node is equal to 0:
                proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Failed to create string_concat call AST node for 'joined with'", jw_op_line, jw_op_column
                Return 0
            End If

            Set left to jw_node
            Continue
        End If

        Note:
        Canonical collection-indexing operator. Three surface forms, all
        equivalent: the bare `X at I` (e.g. `keys at i`), `X at index I`
        (list/array), and `X at key K` (dictionary). The lexer tokenises the
        phrase as the TOKEN_AT keyword (653) optionally followed by the
        TOKEN_INDEX particle (388) or the TOKEN_KEY particle (390). The monolith
        oracle parses this in its primary-postfix loop
        (parser_parse_primary_with_postfix, parser.runa:1166-1185):
        parser_eat(TOKEN_AT), OPTIONALLY eat `index` or `key` if present, parse
        the index sub-expression, and build a `list_get(object, index)` function
        call — the keyword is purely documentary and the bare form is fully
        valid. The oracle's emitted asm for `Let x be xs at i` is a direct
        `call list_get` (object → %rdi, index → %rsi, result → %rax).

        This arm mirrors the oracle exactly: it desugars every form to a
        `list_get(left, index)` call built from a "list_get" identifier callee
        plus a two-element positional argument list — the same already-proven
        call-desugar path used by joined-with (string_concat) and length-of
        (string_length). list_get
        (compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa:185) is a real
        runtime callable that the HIR lowers as an ordinary direct call, so no
        new AST node type or lowering case is introduced. List indexing versus
        dictionary keying is resolved downstream by the runtime type of the
        indexed object, exactly as in the oracle.

        Placement and precedence: the oracle binds `at`-indexing at the
        postfix/primary tier — tighter than every arithmetic operator — so
        `xs at index i plus 1` parses as `(xs at index i) plus 1` (the oracle's
        emitted asm loads `i` alone, calls list_get, then `addq $1`, confirming
        the index operand stops before `plus`). To replicate this, the `at`
        arm runs before the generic binary-operator dispatch (so it always
        applies to the already-parsed `left` regardless of the caller's
        precedence floor) and parses the index sub-expression at
        PRECEDENCE_UNARY (12), the tightest binding level, so the index does
        not greedily absorb a trailing additive/comparison operator.
        :End Note
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_AT:
            Note: Capture the operator position (the TOKEN_AT keyword) before
            Note: consuming the phrase tokens.
            Let at_op_line be proc token_get_line from Parser with current_token
            Let at_op_column be proc token_get_column from Parser with current_token

            Note: Consume "at".
            proc parser_consume_token from Parser with parser

            Note: Optionally consume an `index` or `key` particle. The oracle
            Note: (parser.runa:1171-1179) treats both as OPTIONAL: the bare
            Note: form `X at I` is a valid indexing expression (e.g. `keys at i`)
            Note: and lowers to the same list_get(X, I) call as `X at index I`
            Note: and `X at key K`. When the particle is present it is consumed;
            Note: when absent the index sub-expression is parsed directly off
            Note: the `at`. List indexing versus dictionary keying is resolved
            Note: downstream by the runtime type of the indexed object, exactly
            Note: as in the oracle — the surface keyword is purely documentary.
            Let at_particle_token be proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser
            Let at_particle_type be proc token_get_type from Parser with at_particle_token
            If at_particle_type is equal to TOKEN_INDEX:
                proc parser_consume_token from Parser with parser
            Otherwise If at_particle_type is equal to TOKEN_KEY:
                proc parser_consume_token from Parser with parser
            End If

            Note: Parse the index sub-expression at PRECEDENCE_UNARY so the
            Note: index binds at the tightest tier — `xs at index i plus 1`
            Note: becomes `(xs at index i) plus 1`, mirroring the oracle.
            Let at_index_expr be proc parse_expression_with_precedence with parser, PRECEDENCE_UNARY
            If at_index_expr is equal to 0:
                proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Expected index expression after 'at index'/'at key'", at_op_line, at_op_column
                Return 0
            End If

            Note: Desugar to list_get(left, at_index_expr): a "list_get"
            Note: identifier callee plus a two-element positional argument list,
            Note: built exactly like the joined-with string_concat builder above.
            Note: This is the oracle's lowering target — the monolith's codegen
            Note: emits `call list_get` for EXPR_ARRAY_INDEX (verified against
            Note: the oracle asm for `Let x be xs at index i`: push index /
            Note: push object / pop %rdi / pop %rsi / call list_get). list_get
            Note: (compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa:185) is a
            Note: real runtime callable, and the HIR lowers a direct call to it
            Note: with no specialized node, so this reuses the already-proven
            Note: call-desugar path used by joined-with and length-of.
            Let at_callee be proc build_identifier_node from ASTBuilder with proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "list_get", at_op_line, at_op_column
            If at_callee is equal to 0:
                proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Failed to create list_get callee identifier AST node", at_op_line, at_op_column
                Return 0
            End If
            Let at_args be proc create from List
            If at_args is equal to 0:
                proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Failed to create list_get argument list", at_op_line, at_op_column
                Return 0
            End If
            proc list_append from List with at_args, left
            proc list_append from List with at_args, at_index_expr
            Let at_node be proc build_call_expression from ASTBuilder with at_callee, at_args, 2, at_op_line, at_op_column
            If at_node is equal to 0:
                proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Failed to create list_get call AST node for 'at index'/'at key'", at_op_line, at_op_column
                Return 0
            End If

            Set left to at_node
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Check if current token is a binary operator
        Let is_binary be proc is_binary_operator from Precedence with token_type
        If is_binary is equal to 0:
            Break  Note: Not a binary operator, done parsing
        End If

        Note: Get operator precedence
        Let precedence be proc get_operator_precedence from Precedence with token_type

        Note: If precedence less than minimum, stop parsing
        If precedence is less than min_precedence:
            Break
        End If

        Note:
        With-call argument context exclusion (symbolic comparison/equality).
        The bitwise tiers (3-5) must keep composing inside a with-argument
        (123 self-host sites use forms like `with r_bytes, 3, m3 bitwise_and 15`),
        so the floor stays at PRECEDENCE_WITH_ARGUMENT_LEVEL (3) rather than
        being raised above comparison. That floor admits bitwise but, being
        below comparison/equality numerically, would also admit the symbolic
        `==`/`!=` (PRECEDENCE_EQUALITY, 6) and `<`/`>`/`<=`/`>=`
        (PRECEDENCE_COMPARISON, 7) operators. Those must NOT bind inside an
        argument (matching the monolith's arg chain, which skips both tiers),
        so terminate the argument when one is seen at the with-argument floor.
        :End Note
        If min_precedence is equal to PRECEDENCE_WITH_ARGUMENT_LEVEL:
            If precedence is equal to PRECEDENCE_EQUALITY_OP:
                Break
            End If
            If precedence is equal to PRECEDENCE_COMPARISON_OP:
                Break
            End If
        End If

        Note: Check associativity for equal precedence
        If precedence is equal to min_precedence:
            Let assoc be proc get_operator_associativity from Precedence with token_type
            Note: If right-associative (assoc = 1), stop parsing
            If assoc is equal to 1:
                Break
            End If
        End If

        Note: Parse binary expression with this operator
        Set left to proc parse_binary_expression with parser, left, token_type
        If left is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
    End While

    Note: Check for postfix operators (member access, function call, indexing)
    Loop forever:
        Set current_token to proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser
        Set token_type to proc token_get_type from Parser with current_token

        Note: Check for member access (.)
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_DOT:
            Note:
            Module-qualified access in expression position. Two source forms,
            both produced by the bootstrap import system flattening every
            imported function / constant / global into the main program under
            its PLAIN name, so the module qualifier is source-level only and
            resolution keys off the plain name. The monolith oracle (parser.runa
            postfix `.` handler, ~lines 1424-1548) handles BOTH here:

              (1) `Module.method(args)`  -- a module-qualified METHOD CALL
                  (e.g. `Return Dictionary.contains(d, k)`,
                  `Dictionary.size(d)`, `StringUtils.integer_to_string(n)`).
                  The monolith builds an EXPR_QUALIFIED_CALL. The modular AST
                  has no distinct qualified-call node; the `proc method from
                  Module with args` arm (commit 3413b066) represents one as a
                  plain AST_CALL_EXPRESSION whose callee is an AST_IDENTIFIER
                  carrying the PLAIN method name with the module alias stashed
                  on metadata@56. This desugar reuses that EXACT node shape and
                  the existing direct-call HIR lowering.

              (2) `Module.CONSTANT`  -- a module-qualified CONSTANT / enum /
                  global access with NO parentheses (e.g.
                  `CallingConv.CALLING_CONV_AAPCS64`, `MachineCode.SECTION_TEXT`).
                  The monolith rewrites it to a bare variable reference against
                  the merged namespace, retaining the alias. This desugar reuses
                  the existing AST_IDENTIFIER node carrying the PLAIN name with
                  the module alias on metadata@56 -- byte-identical lowering to
                  the `CONSTANT from Module` form already handled by
                  parse_identifier_expression.

            Both names are read by SPELLING via token_can_be_identifier so
            keyword-typed names (contains/size/remove) and uppercase constants
            are accepted. The whole handler is gated so it fires ONLY when left
            is a bare AST_IDENTIFIER whose first character is uppercase A-Z
            (module-name convention, matching the `X from Module` guard) and the
            token after the dot can name an identifier. Any miss falls through
            to the unchanged parse_member_expression path, so plain
            lowercase-object `obj.field` member access is untouched. Reusing the
            qualified-call / qualified-identifier nodes means NO new node kind
            and NO new HIR/MIR lowering is introduced.
            :End Note
            Let qmc_handled be 0
            If left is not equal to 0:
                Let qmc_left_type be proc ast_node_get_type from AST with left
                If qmc_left_type is equal to AST_IDENTIFIER from AST:
                    Let qmc_module_name be proc ast_node_get_value from AST with left
                    Let qmc_module_is_name be 0
                    If qmc_module_name is not equal to 0:
                        Let qmc_first_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with qmc_module_name, 0
                        If qmc_first_char is greater than or equal to 65:
                            If qmc_first_char is less than or equal to 90:
                                Set qmc_module_is_name to 1
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                    If qmc_module_is_name is equal to 1:
                        Let qmc_name_token be proc parser_peek_token from Parser with parser, 1
                        Let qmc_name_ok be 0
                        If qmc_name_token is not equal to 0:
                            Let qmc_name_type be proc token_get_type from Parser with qmc_name_token
                            Let qmc_name_can_id be proc token_can_be_identifier from Parser with qmc_name_type
                            If qmc_name_can_id is equal to 1:
                                Set qmc_name_ok to 1
                            End If
                        End If
                        If qmc_name_ok is equal to 1:
                            Let qmc_member_value be proc token_get_value from Parser with qmc_name_token
                            Let qmc_acc_line be proc token_get_line from Parser with qmc_name_token
                            Let qmc_acc_column be proc token_get_column from Parser with qmc_name_token
                            Let qmc_paren_token be proc parser_peek_token from Parser with parser, 2
                            Let qmc_is_call be 0
                            If qmc_paren_token is not equal to 0:
                                Let qmc_paren_type be proc token_get_type from Parser with qmc_paren_token
                                If qmc_paren_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN:
                                    Set qmc_is_call to 1
                                End If
                            End If

                            Note: Consume the dot and the member-name token (shared
                            Note: by both the call and the constant-access forms).
                            proc parser_consume_token from Parser with parser
                            proc parser_consume_token from Parser with parser

                            If qmc_is_call is equal to 1:
                                Note: Form (1): `Module.method(args)`. Consume '(' and
                                Note: parse the comma-separated argument list.
                                proc parser_consume_token from Parser with parser
                                Let qmc_arguments be proc parse_argument_list with parser
                                If qmc_arguments is equal to 0:
                                    Set qmc_arguments to proc create from List
                                End If
                                Let qmc_rparen be proc parser_expect_token from Parser with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
                                If qmc_rparen is equal to 0:
                                    Return 0
                                End If
                                Let qmc_callee be proc build_identifier_node from ASTBuilder with qmc_member_value, qmc_acc_line, qmc_acc_column
                                If qmc_callee is equal to 0:
                                    proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Failed to create qualified method-call callee identifier AST node", qmc_acc_line, qmc_acc_column
                                    Return 0
                                End If
                                Let qmc_call_alias be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with qmc_module_name
                                If qmc_call_alias is not equal to 0:
                                    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with qmc_callee, 56, qmc_call_alias
                                End If
                                Let qmc_argument_count be proc list_length from List with qmc_arguments
                                Let qmc_call_node be proc build_call_expression from ASTBuilder with qmc_callee, qmc_arguments, qmc_argument_count, qmc_acc_line, qmc_acc_column
                                If qmc_call_node is equal to 0:
                                    proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Failed to create qualified method-call expression AST node", qmc_acc_line, qmc_acc_column
                                    Return 0
                                End If
                                proc destroy_ast_node from AST with left
                                Set left to qmc_call_node
                                Set qmc_handled to 1
                            Otherwise:
                                Note: Form (2): `Module.CONSTANT` (no parens). Build a
                                Note: bare identifier carrying the PLAIN member name with
                                Note: the module alias on metadata@56 -- identical to the
                                Note: `CONSTANT from Module` rvalue node.
                                Let qmc_const_node be proc build_identifier_node from ASTBuilder with qmc_member_value, qmc_acc_line, qmc_acc_column
                                If qmc_const_node is equal to 0:
                                    proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Failed to create qualified constant-access identifier AST node", qmc_acc_line, qmc_acc_column
                                    Return 0
                                End If
                                Let qmc_const_alias be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with qmc_module_name
                                If qmc_const_alias is not equal to 0:
                                    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with qmc_const_node, 56, qmc_const_alias
                                End If
                                proc destroy_ast_node from AST with left
                                Set left to qmc_const_node
                                Set qmc_handled to 1
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
            If qmc_handled is equal to 1:
                Continue
            End If
            Set left to proc parse_member_expression with parser, left
            If left is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Check for function call (()
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN:
            Set left to proc parse_call_expression with parser, left
            If left is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Check for canonical named-call argument clause (`callee with arg
        Note: [and arg] [, arg] ...`). This is the primary Runa call surface
        Note: form: `helper with 41`, `add with 20 and 22`. The opening "with"
        Note: promotes the parsed callee expression into a function call whose
        Note: arguments follow. Handled as a postfix operator so chained forms
        Note: (`obj.method with x`) and qualified callees compose naturally.
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_WITH:
            Set left to proc parse_with_call_arguments with parser, left
            If left is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Check for array indexing ([])
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET:
            Set left to proc parse_index_expression with parser, left
            If left is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Check for range operator (..)
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_RANGE:
            Set left to proc parse_range_expression with parser, left
            If left is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Check for "sorted by" operator (Language Additions v0.0.8.5)
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SORTED:
            Set left to proc parse_sorted_expression with parser, left
            If left is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
            Continue
        End If

        Note: No more postfix operators, done
        Break
    End While

    Return left
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: DEC-0018 Layer 3 — Contextual Aggregation Disambiguation
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "is_expression_head" takes token_kind as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Fixed token-class membership test: does token_kind begin a primary
    expression operand? This is the bounded, scope-free predicate DEC-0018
    Layer 3 uses to decide whether a bare aggregation word reads as the
    aggregation OPERATOR. It mirrors EXACTLY the set of token kinds that
    parse_primary_expression (and the unary-prefix arm of the Pratt loop)
    accept as the first token of an operand. It performs no source rescan
    and consults no scope — it is a constant-time discriminant test.

    The expression-head class is:
      - Literals: string/raw/formatted-string (100-102), numeric (110-114),
        boolean (120-121), null/none/nil (130-132), character (140).
      - Identifier (150).
      - Grouping / collection openers: '(' (200), '[' (204).
      - f-string prefix (102, already covered by formatted-string).
      - Pipeline / selection / aggregation keyword expression-starters:
        Filter (329), the five aggregation words (335-339), first/last
        (345/346), Group (349), Transform (357).
      - Function-pointer '$' (654) and indirect-call 'proc' (440).
      - Any unary prefix operator (not / negative / positive / bitwise-not),
        delegated to Precedence.is_unary_operator.

    Returns 1 if token_kind can begin an expression operand, 0 otherwise.
    :End Note

    Note: Literals
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_STRING_LITERAL:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_RAW_STRING_LITERAL:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_FORMATTED_STRING_LITERAL:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_INTEGER_LITERAL:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_FLOAT_LITERAL:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_HEX_LITERAL:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_BINARY_LITERAL:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_OCTAL_LITERAL:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_BOOLEAN_TRUE:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_BOOLEAN_FALSE:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_NULL:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_NONE:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_NIL:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_CHARACTER_LITERAL:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Identifier
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Contextual keywords that are identifier-eligible (e.g. `left`, `right`,
    Note: `shifted`, `xor`, `bitwise`, `count`, `index`, ...) also begin an operand
    Note: when they appear in primary position — parse_primary_expression now
    Note: routes them to parse_identifier_expression. Keeping this predicate in
    Note: lock-step with that dispatch ensures the DEC-0018 binder RHS-completeness
    Note: gate (and the aggregation two-token gate) treat `Let x be left` as a
    Note: complete RHS rather than a mis-parse.
    Let kw_id_head be proc token_can_be_identifier from Parser with token_kind
    If kw_id_head is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Grouping / collection openers
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_F_STRING:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Pipeline / selection / aggregation keyword expression-starters
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_FILTER:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_AVERAGE:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_SUM:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_COUNT:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_MINIMUM:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_MAXIMUM:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_FIRST:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_LAST:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_GROUP:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_TRANSFORM:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Function-pointer and indirect-call openers
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_DOLLAR:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_kind is equal to TOKEN_PROC:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Unary prefix operators (delegated to the precedence table so the two
    Note: recognition paths never diverge).
    Let unary_head be proc is_unary_operator from Precedence with token_kind
    If unary_head is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "aggregation_word_is_operator" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    DEC-0018 Layer 3 two-token gate. The current token is one of the five
    aggregation words (already known by the caller). This decides whether it
    reads as the aggregation OPERATOR or as a bare identifier.

    Rule (scope-free, O(1), bounded 2-token lookahead, no source rescan):
      operator iff  peek(1) is TOKEN_OF  AND  is_expression_head(peek(2)).

    Otherwise the word is an identifier. This is exactly why bare single-word
    `count` / `sum` used as identifiers keep working everywhere they are not
    followed by `of <expr>`.

    Returns 1 if the aggregation word should parse as the operator, 0 if it
    should be demoted to an identifier.
    :End Note

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let next_token be proc parser_peek_token from Parser with parser, 1
    If next_token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let next_kind be proc token_get_type from Parser with next_token
    If next_kind is not equal to TOKEN_OF:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let after_of_token be proc parser_peek_token from Parser with parser, 2
    If after_of_token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let after_of_kind be proc token_get_type from Parser with after_of_token
    Return proc is_expression_head with after_of_kind
End Process

Process called "first_last_word_is_operator" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Selection-keyword two-token gate, the first/last analogue of
    aggregation_word_is_operator. The current token is TOKEN_FIRST or
    TOKEN_LAST (already known by the caller). This decides whether it reads as
    the SELECTION operator (`first N items ...`, `last item ...`) or as a bare
    identifier (a variable named `first` / `last`, which the monolith always
    permits because it never lexed these as keywords).

    Rule (scope-free, O(1), bounded 1-token lookahead, no source rescan):
      operator iff  peek(1) begins a count operand — a numeric literal, the
      word `item` (count = 1), or any other expression-head token that the
      selection grammar parses as the count expression.

    The selection grammar (parse_first_last_expression) consumes the keyword
    then REQUIRES a count expression or the `item` word; if `first` / `last`
    is followed by anything that cannot begin that count operand (a statement
    terminator, a binary operator, `End`, `,`, `)`, etc.) it is being used as a
    plain identifier and must be demoted. Returns 1 for the operator reading, 0
    for the identifier reading.
    :End Note

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let next_token be proc parser_peek_token from Parser with parser, 1
    If next_token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let next_kind be proc token_get_type from Parser with next_token

    Note: `first item` / `last item` — the singular-count selection form.
    If next_kind is equal to TOKEN_ITEM:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: `first <count> [items] ...` — any expression-head count operand. This
    Note: covers numeric literals (the common case) and parenthesised / variable
    Note: count expressions, exactly the set parse_first_last_expression's
    Note: parse_expression call would accept as the count.
    Return proc is_expression_head with next_kind
End Process

Process called "demote_aggregation_to_identifier" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    DEC-0018 Layer 3 fallback. An aggregation word that the two-token gate
    did NOT classify as the operator is a plain identifier. The lexer stores
    the word's spelling in the token's value field (offset 8) even for hard
    keyword tokens, so the identifier name is read directly from the current
    token. One AST identifier node is built and the single token consumed —
    no source rescan, no extra allocation beyond the AST node itself.

    Returns the identifier AST node, or 0 on error.
    :End Note

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let current_token be proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser
    If current_token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let token_value be proc token_get_value from Parser with current_token
    If token_value is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let token_line be proc token_get_line from Parser with current_token
    Let token_column be proc token_get_column from Parser with current_token

    Let identifier_node be proc build_identifier_node from ASTBuilder with token_value, token_line, token_column
    If identifier_node is equal to 0:
        proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Failed to create identifier AST node for aggregation word used as identifier", token_line, token_column
        Return 0
    End If

    proc parser_consume_token from Parser with parser
    Return identifier_node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Primary Expression Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "parse_primary_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Parse a primary expression (literal, identifier, parenthesized)
    
    Parameters:
      parser - Pointer to ParserState
    
    Returns:
      Pointer to primary expression AST node
      Returns 0 on parsing error
    
    Primary expressions:
      - Literals: strings, numbers, booleans, null
      - Identifiers: variables, functions, types
      - Parenthesized: (expression)
      - String interpolation: f"text {expr}" (v0.0.8.5)
      - Array literals: [expr1, expr2, ...]
      - Tuple literals: (expr1, expr2, ...)
    
    Algorithm:
    1. Check current token type
    2. If literal: call parse_literal_expression
    3. If identifier: call parse_identifier_expression
    4. If left parenthesis: call parse_parenthesized_expression
    5. If string with f prefix: call parse_interpolated_string
    6. If left bracket: call parse_array_literal
    7. Otherwise: report error and return 0
    :End Note

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let current_token be proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser
    Let token_type be proc token_get_type from Parser with current_token

    Note:
    Unary minus in primary position. The lexer emits the symbolic `-` as
    TOKEN_MINUS (501), which the precedence table registers as a BINARY
    additive operator (is_binary=1, precedence.runa:304). It is therefore NOT
    routed through the generic unary-prefix arm of the Pratt loop
    (is_unary_operator returns 0 for it), so a leading `-` falls through to
    this primary parser. Mirror the monolith oracle (parser.runa
    parser_parse_primary, "Handle unary minus for negative numbers"): consume
    the `-`, parse the operand as a primary, and desugar to the binary
    expression `0 - operand`. This reuses the already-lowered binary
    subtraction path (TOKEN_MINUS -> additive MIR -> LIR_SUB) and the existing
    build_integer_literal / build_binary_expression builders, so no new AST
    node, HIR lowering, or codegen is required. `0 - 1` evaluates to -1,
    matching `Return -1`, `Let x be -3`, `Constant C as Integer is -1`, and
    composes inside larger expressions (`a plus -1`, `-1 plus a`) because the
    desugared node is an ordinary expression returned to the Pratt loop.
    :End Note
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_MINUS:
        Let neg_line be proc token_get_line from Parser with current_token
        Let neg_column be proc token_get_column from Parser with current_token

        Note: Consume the `-`.
        proc parser_consume_token from Parser with parser

        Note: Parse the operand as a primary so the minus binds only the
        Note: immediately-following primary (literal / variable / grouping),
        Note: exactly like the monolith's parser_parse_primary recursion.
        Let neg_operand be proc parse_primary_expression with parser
        If neg_operand is equal to 0:
            proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Expected expression after unary minus", neg_line, neg_column
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Zero literal as the left operand of the subtraction.
        Let neg_zero be proc build_integer_literal from ASTBuilder with 0, neg_line, neg_column
        If neg_zero is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        Let neg_node be proc build_binary_expression from ASTBuilder with TOKEN_MINUS, neg_zero, neg_operand, neg_line, neg_column
        If neg_node is equal to 0:
            proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Failed to create unary minus AST node", neg_line, neg_column
            Return 0
        End If
        Return neg_node
    End If

    Note:
    Canonical word-form negation. The lexer tokenises the literal word
    "negative" as TOKEN_NEGATIVE (307). In expression-primary position
    "negative <INTEGER>" is the negative-integer-literal form (mirroring the
    monolith's parser_parse_primary TOKEN_NEGATIVE branch, Bug #371): fold it
    to a single integer literal carrying the negated value via the existing
    build_integer_literal builder. When TOKEN_NEGATIVE is NOT followed by an
    integer literal it is being used as an ordinary identifier ("negative" is
    identifier-eligible so `Let negative be 0` and references to it must parse);
    in that case fall through to the generic identifier dispatch below WITHOUT
    consuming the token here.
    :End Note
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_NEGATIVE:
        Let neg_lit_next be proc parser_peek_token from Parser with parser, 1
        Let neg_lit_next_type be 0
        If neg_lit_next is not equal to 0:
            Set neg_lit_next_type to proc token_get_type from Parser with neg_lit_next
        End If
        If neg_lit_next_type is equal to TOKEN_INTEGER_LITERAL:
            Let neg_lit_line be proc token_get_line from Parser with current_token
            Let neg_lit_column be proc token_get_column from Parser with current_token

            Note: Read the magnitude from the following integer literal, negate it,
            Note: and consume both the "negative" word and the integer token.
            Let neg_lit_value_str be proc token_get_value from Parser with neg_lit_next
            Let neg_lit_magnitude be proc string_to_integer from StringPrimitive with neg_lit_value_str
            Let neg_lit_value be 0 minus neg_lit_magnitude

            Note: Consume "negative".
            proc parser_consume_token from Parser with parser
            Note: Consume the integer literal.
            proc parser_consume_token from Parser with parser

            Let neg_lit_node be proc build_integer_literal from ASTBuilder with neg_lit_value, neg_lit_line, neg_lit_column
            If neg_lit_node is equal to 0:
                proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Failed to create negative integer literal node", neg_lit_line, neg_lit_column
                Return 0
            End If
            Return neg_lit_node
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check for literals (string, number, boolean, null, character).
    Note: The literal token-type constants form the lexical literal class:
    Note:   string 100-102, numeric 110-114, boolean 120-121, null/none/nil 130-132, character 140.
    Let is_literal be 0
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_STRING_LITERAL:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_RAW_STRING_LITERAL:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_FORMATTED_STRING_LITERAL:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_INTEGER_LITERAL:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_FLOAT_LITERAL:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_HEX_LITERAL:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_BINARY_LITERAL:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_OCTAL_LITERAL:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_BOOLEAN_TRUE:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_BOOLEAN_FALSE:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_NULL:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_NONE:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_NIL:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_CHARACTER_LITERAL:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If is_literal is equal to 1:
        Return proc parse_literal_expression with parser
    End If

    Note: Check for canonical collection literal. Two surface forms reach the parser as
    Note: the SAME canonical token shape:
    Note:   - Source canonical "a list containing e1, e2, ...": article and "list" lex as
    Note:     identifiers, "containing" as TOKEN_CONTAINING (keyword table).
    Note:   - Bracketed "[e1, e2, ...]": the syntax transformer rewrites it to the token
    Note:     sequence a / list / containing / elements, BUT synthesises "containing" as a
    Note:     plain identifier (create_identifier_token), not the keyword token.
    Note:   - Empty "[]": transformer rewrites to "an empty list" (three identifiers, no
    Note:     "containing").
    Note: The article ("a"/"an") and "list"/"empty" all lex as TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, so this
    Note: is detected by token-value lookahead before the generic identifier branch.
    Note: "containing" is accepted as TOKEN_CONTAINING OR an identifier valued "containing"
    Note: so both the source and the transformed bracket form route here. Only the list
    Note: form lowers end-to-end today; dictionary/set literals have no HIR lowering and
    Note: are intentionally not intercepted (they would otherwise produce dropped output).
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
        Let cl_is_article be proc primary_token_value_is with current_token, "a"
        If cl_is_article is equal to 0:
            Set cl_is_article to proc primary_token_value_is with current_token, "an"
        End If
        If cl_is_article is equal to 1:
            Let cl_next be proc parser_peek_token from Parser with parser, 1

            Note: Empty-list form: "an empty list".
            Let cl_next_is_empty be proc primary_token_value_is with cl_next, "empty"
            If cl_next_is_empty is equal to 1:
                Let cl_after_empty be proc parser_peek_token from Parser with parser, 2
                Let cl_after_empty_is_list be proc primary_token_value_is with cl_after_empty, "list"
                If cl_after_empty_is_list is equal to 1:
                    Return proc parse_canonical_empty_list_literal with parser
                End If
            End If

            Note: Non-empty list form: "a list containing ...".
            Let cl_next_is_list be proc primary_token_value_is with cl_next, "list"
            If cl_next_is_list is equal to 1:
                Let cl_after be proc parser_peek_token from Parser with parser, 2
                Let cl_after_type be proc token_get_type from Parser with cl_after
                Let cl_after_is_containing be 0
                If cl_after_type is equal to TOKEN_CONTAINING:
                    Set cl_after_is_containing to 1
                End If
                If cl_after_is_containing is equal to 0:
                    Set cl_after_is_containing to proc primary_token_value_is with cl_after, "containing"
                End If
                If cl_after_is_containing is equal to 1:
                    Return proc parse_canonical_list_literal with parser
                End If
            End If

            Note: Struct constructor form: "a value of type TypeName [with ...]". The
            Note: word "value" lexes as an identifier; the following "of" confirms the
            Note: constructor rather than a plain variable named "value". Without this
            Note: the article path falls through to the generic identifier branch and
            Note: "value of type T" is left dangling, dropping the whole statement.
            Let cl_next_is_value be proc primary_token_value_is with cl_next, "value"
            If cl_next_is_value is equal to 1:
                Let cl_after_value be proc parser_peek_token from Parser with parser, 2
                Let cl_after_value_type be proc token_get_type from Parser with cl_after_value
                If cl_after_value_type is equal to TOKEN_OF:
                    Return proc parse_a_value_of_type_construction with parser
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note:
    `length of <collection>` aggregation/length operator (prefix form).
    Mirrors the monolith oracle exactly (parser.runa parser_parse_primary,
    "Handle length of X → string_length(X)"): when the word `length` is
    immediately followed by the `of` particle it reads as the length
    operator and desugars to a call to the runtime `string_length`
    function with the collection as its sole positional argument; otherwise
    `length` is a bare variable reference and falls through to the generic
    identifier branch below. The modular lexer never lexed `length` as a
    dedicated keyword (the monolith used TOKEN_LENGTH=151), so it arrives
    here as a plain TOKEN_IDENTIFIER whose value is "length"; the
    discriminant is therefore a value compare plus a single TOKEN_OF
    lookahead, identical in shape to the canonical-list / value-of-type
    article gates above and the aggregation-word two-token gate.
    .
    The desugar reuses the existing AST_CALL_EXPRESSION node and its HIR
    call lowering (no new node kind, no new lowering layer), exactly as the
    monolith emits `expression_create_function_call("string_length", ...)`
    and the codegen maps TOKEN_STRING_LENGTH to a `call string_length`.
    The operand is parsed at PRECEDENCE_UNARY so it binds a single primary
    (with any postfix the loop applies at that tightness) and does not
    swallow a trailing lower-precedence infix operator, matching the
    monolith's parser_parse_primary_with_postfix operand scope.
    :End Note
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
        Let len_is_length be proc primary_token_value_is with current_token, "length"
        If len_is_length is equal to 1:
            Let len_peek be proc parser_peek_token from Parser with parser, 1
            Let len_peek_type be proc token_get_type from Parser with len_peek
            If len_peek_type is equal to TOKEN_OF:
                Let len_op_line be proc token_get_line from Parser with current_token
                Let len_op_column be proc token_get_column from Parser with current_token

                Note: Consume `length` then the mandatory `of` particle.
                proc parser_consume_token from Parser with parser
                proc parser_consume_token from Parser with parser

                Note: Parse the collection operand one level tighter than any
                Note: infix operator so `length of a plus b` reads as
                Note: (string_length(a)) plus b, mirroring the monolith primary.
                Let len_operand be proc parse_expression_with_precedence with parser, PRECEDENCE_UNARY
                If len_operand is equal to 0:
                    proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Expected expression after 'length of'", len_op_line, len_op_column
                    Return 0
                End If

                Note: Desugar to string_length(operand): a "string_length"
                Note: identifier callee plus a one-element positional argument
                Note: list, mirroring the joined-with string_concat builder and
                Note: the monolith's expression_create_function_call.
                Let len_callee be proc build_identifier_node from ASTBuilder with proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "string_length", len_op_line, len_op_column
                If len_callee is equal to 0:
                    proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Failed to create string_length callee identifier AST node", len_op_line, len_op_column
                    Return 0
                End If
                Let len_args be proc create from List
                If len_args is equal to 0:
                    proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Failed to create string_length argument list", len_op_line, len_op_column
                    Return 0
                End If
                proc list_append from List with len_args, len_operand
                Let len_node be proc build_call_expression from ASTBuilder with len_callee, len_args, 1, len_op_line, len_op_column
                If len_node is equal to 0:
                    proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Failed to create string_length call AST node for 'length of'", len_op_line, len_op_column
                    Return 0
                End If
                Return len_node
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check for identifier
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
        Return proc parse_identifier_expression with parser
    End If

    Note: Check for left parenthesis (parenthesized expression or tuple)
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN:
        Return proc parse_parenthesized_expression with parser
    End If

    Note: Check for left bracket (array literal)
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET:
        Return proc parse_array_literal with parser
    End If

    Note: Check for f-string prefix (string interpolation)
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_F_STRING:
        Return proc parse_interpolated_string with parser
    End If

    Note: Check for Filter keyword (Language Additions v0.0.8.5)
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_FILTER:
        Return proc parse_filter_expression with parser
    End If

    Note: Check for aggregation keywords (Language Additions v0.0.8.5).
    Note: DEC-0018 Layer 3: each aggregation word reads as the aggregation
    Note: OPERATOR only when the two-token gate (next token is `of` AND the
    Note: token after `of` begins an expression) holds; otherwise it is a bare
    Note: identifier and is demoted. This is scope-free, O(1), no source rescan.
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_AVERAGE:
        Let avg_is_operator be proc aggregation_word_is_operator with parser
        If avg_is_operator is equal to 1:
            Return proc parse_aggregation_expression with parser, TOKEN_AVERAGE
        End If
        Return proc demote_aggregation_to_identifier with parser
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SUM:
        Let sum_is_operator be proc aggregation_word_is_operator with parser
        If sum_is_operator is equal to 1:
            Return proc parse_aggregation_expression with parser, TOKEN_SUM
        End If
        Return proc demote_aggregation_to_identifier with parser
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_COUNT:
        Let count_is_operator be proc aggregation_word_is_operator with parser
        If count_is_operator is equal to 1:
            Return proc parse_aggregation_expression with parser, TOKEN_COUNT
        End If
        Return proc demote_aggregation_to_identifier with parser
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_MINIMUM:
        Let min_is_operator be proc aggregation_word_is_operator with parser
        If min_is_operator is equal to 1:
            Return proc parse_aggregation_expression with parser, TOKEN_MINIMUM
        End If
        Return proc demote_aggregation_to_identifier with parser
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_MAXIMUM:
        Let max_is_operator be proc aggregation_word_is_operator with parser
        If max_is_operator is equal to 1:
            Return proc parse_aggregation_expression with parser, TOKEN_MAXIMUM
        End If
        Return proc demote_aggregation_to_identifier with parser
    End If

    Note: Check for first/last selection keywords (Language Additions v0.0.8.5).
    Note: Gated by the two-token discriminant: `first` / `last` reads as the
    Note: selection operator only when followed by a count operand or the word
    Note: `item`; otherwise it is a bare variable named `first` / `last` and is
    Note: demoted to an identifier (mirrors the monolith, which never lexed these
    Note: as keywords, and the aggregation-word demotion pattern above).
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_FIRST:
        Let first_is_operator be proc first_last_word_is_operator with parser
        If first_is_operator is equal to 1:
            Return proc parse_first_last_expression with parser, TOKEN_FIRST
        End If
        Return proc demote_aggregation_to_identifier with parser
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LAST:
        Let last_is_operator be proc first_last_word_is_operator with parser
        If last_is_operator is equal to 1:
            Return proc parse_first_last_expression with parser, TOKEN_LAST
        End If
        Return proc demote_aggregation_to_identifier with parser
    End If

    Note: Check for Group keyword (Language Additions v0.0.8.5)
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_GROUP:
        Return proc parse_group_expression with parser
    End If

    Note: Check for Transform keyword (Language Additions v0.0.8.5)
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_TRANSFORM:
        Return proc parse_transform_expression with parser
    End If

    Note: Check for $ (function pointer creation)
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_DOLLAR:
        Return proc parse_function_pointer_expression with parser
    End If

    Note: Check for proc (indirect function call)
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PROC:
        Return proc parse_proc_call_expression with parser
    End If

    Note: Keyword-as-identifier fallback. Several contextual keywords double as
    Note: legitimate variable / field names (`left`, `right`, `shifted`, `xor`,
    Note: `bitwise`, `count`, `index`, `key`, ...). When such a token reaches the
    Note: PRIMARY position it is the head of an operand — i.e. a variable
    Note: REFERENCE — not an operator (the word-operator forms like `a shifted
    Note: left by 2` are consumed by the infix/precedence loop on the LEFT operand
    Note: before primary parsing re-enters, so they never arrive here). This gate
    Note: is placed LAST so every specific keyword dispatch above (aggregation,
    Note: first/last, group, transform, proc, ...) takes priority; only a bare
    Note: identifier-eligible keyword falls through to be parsed as an identifier.
    Note: Mirrors the monolith's token_can_be_identifier dispatch in
    Note: parser_parse_primary. Without this, `Return left` fails and panic-mode
    Note: recovery drops every following declaration.
    Let id_eligible be proc token_can_be_identifier from Parser with token_type
    If id_eligible is equal to 1:
        Return proc parse_identifier_expression with parser
    End If

    Note: Unexpected token - report error
    proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Expected primary expression (literal, identifier, or parenthesized expression)", proc token_get_line from Parser with proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser, proc token_get_column from Parser with proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser
    Return 0
End Process

