Note: ============================================================================
Note: Function Call Expression Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "parse_call_expression" takes parser as Integer, callee as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse a function call expression
    Note: .
    Note: Parameters:
    Note:   parser - Pointer to ParserState
    Note:   callee - Pointer to function/object being called
    Note: .
    Note: Returns:
    Note:   Pointer to call expression AST node
    Note:   Returns 0 on parsing error
    Note: .
    Note: Algorithm:
    Note: 1. Expect and consume left parenthesis
    Note: 2. Parse argument list:
    Note:    - If right parenthesis immediately: empty arguments
    Note:    - Otherwise: parse comma-separated expressions
    Note: 3. Expect and consume right parenthesis
    Note: 4. Create call expression AST node using ASTBuilder.build_call_expression
    Note: 5. Return call expression AST node

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If callee is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Capture the call position from the opening parenthesis token.
    Let call_token be proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser
    Let call_line be proc token_get_line from Parser with call_token
    Let call_column be proc token_get_column from Parser with call_token

    Note: Expect and consume left parenthesis
    Let result be proc parser_expect_token from Parser with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN
    If result is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Parse argument list
    Let arguments be proc parse_argument_list with parser

    If arguments is equal to 0:
        Note: Empty argument list is valid, create empty list
        Set arguments to proc create from List
    End If

    Note: Expect and consume right parenthesis
    Set result to proc parser_expect_token from Parser with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
    If result is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Build call expression AST node
    Let argument_count be proc list_length from List with arguments
    Let call_node be proc build_call_expression from ASTBuilder with callee, arguments, argument_count, call_line, call_column

    If call_node is equal to 0:
        proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Failed to create call expression AST node", proc token_get_line from Parser with proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser, proc token_get_column from Parser with proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser
        Return 0
    End If

    Return call_node
End Process

Process called "parse_with_call_arguments" takes parser as Integer, callee as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Canonical Runa expresses a function call as `callee with arg [and arg]
    [, arg] ...` — the primary call surface form (`helper with 41`,
    `add with 20 and 22`, `f with a, b, c`). The lexer emits the connective as
    TOKEN_WITH; this handler runs as a postfix operator once the callee
    expression has been parsed, consuming the argument clause and promoting the
    callee into an AST_CALL_EXPRESSION. It mirrors the stage1 monolith's
    with-clause promotion (parser.runa with_promote_to_call_or_lambda) so that
    self-hosting source which uses the canonical call form lowers identically.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Consume the leading "with".
    2. Parse the first argument with parse_expression_with_precedence at
       PRECEDENCE_WITH_ARGUMENT_LEVEL so the per-argument Pratt parse stops at
       the "and"/"," separators (logical-and/or sit below that floor) yet still
       composes comparison and arithmetic within a single argument.
    3. Support the named-argument surface form `name as value`: when the parsed
       argument is a bare identifier immediately followed by "as", re-parse the
       value expression and keep the VALUE as the positional argument (HIR call
       lowering is positional — it reads the arguments List in order from
       offset 88 and ignores parameter names), matching the monolith's codegen
       behaviour.
    4. Continue while the next token is "and" (TOKEN_AND) or "," (TOKEN_COMMA):
       consume the separator and parse the next argument the same way.
    5. Build the call node via ASTBuilder.build_call_expression (callee at
       offset 80, arguments List at 88, count at 96 — the same node the paren
       call form produces, so AST_CALL_EXPRESSION lowering is shared).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Linear in the argument count; one List allocation per call site. Cold
    relative to the per-token Pratt loop it is invoked from.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Pointer-validated at entry. A null argument parse aborts the whole call
    parse (returns 0) so a malformed argument clause cannot yield a partially
    constructed call node with dangling arguments.
    @End Security_Scope

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If callee is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Capture the call position from the "with" token.
    Let with_token be proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser
    Let call_line be proc token_get_line from Parser with with_token
    Let call_column be proc token_get_column from Parser with with_token

    Note: Consume the leading "with".
    proc parser_consume_token from Parser with parser

    Note: Allocate the argument list.
    Let arguments be proc create from List
    If arguments is equal to 0:
        proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Failed to create with-call argument list", proc token_get_line from Parser with proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser, proc token_get_column from Parser with proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser
        Return 0
    End If

    Let argument_count be 0

    Note: Parse the comma/and-separated argument sequence.
    Loop forever:
        Let arg be proc parse_with_single_argument with parser
        If arg is equal to 0:
            proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Expected argument expression after 'with'", proc token_get_line from Parser with proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser, proc token_get_column from Parser with proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser
            Return 0
        End If

        proc list_append from List with arguments, arg
        Set argument_count to argument_count plus 1

        Note: Check for an "and" or "," separator introducing another argument.
        Let sep_token be proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser
        Let sep_type be proc token_get_type from Parser with sep_token

        If sep_type is equal to TOKEN_AND:
            proc parser_consume_token from Parser with parser
            Continue
        End If

        If sep_type is equal to TOKEN_COMMA:
            proc parser_consume_token from Parser with parser
            Continue
        End If

        Note: No further separator: argument clause complete.
        Break
    End While

    Note: Build the call node (shared AST_CALL_EXPRESSION shape with the paren form).
    Let call_node be proc build_call_expression from ASTBuilder with callee, arguments, argument_count, call_line, call_column
    If call_node is equal to 0:
        proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Failed to create with-call expression AST node", proc token_get_line from Parser with proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser, proc token_get_column from Parser with proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser
        Return 0
    End If

    Return call_node
End Process

Process called "parse_with_single_argument" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse exactly one argument inside a canonical "with"-call clause. Factored
    out of parse_with_call_arguments so the first argument and every
    separator-introduced argument share identical parsing (including the
    `name as value` named-argument surface form) with no duplicated logic.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Parse the argument value with parse_expression_with_precedence at
    PRECEDENCE_WITH_ARGUMENT_LEVEL (stops at "and"/"," separators). If the
    parsed value is a bare identifier immediately followed by "as", this is the
    named-argument form `name as value`: consume "as" and parse the real value
    expression, returning the value (HIR call lowering is positional and does
    not consume the name). Otherwise the parsed expression is the positional
    argument.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One Pratt sub-parse per argument; the named-argument lookahead is a single
    token-type comparison.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Returns 0 on any failed sub-parse so the caller aborts the whole call
    rather than building a call with a dangling argument.
    @End Security_Scope

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let value be proc parse_expression_with_precedence with parser, PRECEDENCE_WITH_ARGUMENT_LEVEL
    If value is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Named-argument form: `name as value`. When the parsed expression is a
    Note: bare identifier and the next token is "as", treat the identifier as
    Note: the parameter name and re-parse the value expression. HIR call
    Note: lowering is positional, so we discard the name and keep the value as
    Note: the positional argument.
    Let value_kind be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with value, 0
    If value_kind is equal to AST_IDENTIFIER from AST:
        Let after_token be proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser
        Let after_type be proc token_get_type from Parser with after_token
        If after_type is equal to TOKEN_AS:
            proc parser_consume_token from Parser with parser
            Let named_value be proc parse_expression_with_precedence with parser, PRECEDENCE_WITH_ARGUMENT_LEVEL
            If named_value is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
            Return named_value
        End If
    End If

    Return value
End Process

Process called "parse_argument_list" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse a function call argument list
    Note: .
    Note: Parameters:
    Note:   parser - Pointer to ParserState
    Note: .
    Note: Returns:
    Note:   Pointer to List of argument AST nodes
    Note:   Returns 0 on parsing error
    Note: .
    Note: Algorithm:
    Note: 1. Create empty List for arguments
    Note: 2. While not at right parenthesis:
    Note:    - Parse argument expression using parse_expression
    Note:    - Add to arguments List
    Note:    - If comma found: consume comma and continue
    Note:    - Otherwise: break
    Note: 3. Return arguments List

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check if we have arguments (not immediately at right paren)
    Let current_token be proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser
    Let token_type be proc token_get_type from Parser with current_token

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN:
        Note: Empty argument list
        Return proc create from List
    End If

    Note: Create list for arguments
    Let arguments be proc create from List
    If arguments is equal to 0:
        proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Failed to create argument list", proc token_get_line from Parser with proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser, proc token_get_column from Parser with proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Parse arguments until we hit right parenthesis
    Loop forever:
        Note: Parse argument expression
        Let arg be proc parse_expression with parser

        If arg is equal to 0:
            proc parser_report_error from Parser with parser, 2, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Expected expression in argument list", proc token_get_line from Parser with proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser, proc token_get_column from Parser with proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Add argument to list
        proc list_append from List with arguments, arg

        Note: Check for comma (more arguments) or right paren (done)
        Set current_token to proc parser_current_token from Parser with parser
        Set token_type to proc token_get_type from Parser with current_token

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_COMMA:
            Note: Consume comma and continue to next argument
            proc parser_consume_token from Parser with parser
            Continue
        End If

        Note: No comma, done with arguments
        Break
    End While

    Return arguments
End Process

